# THE DIFFERENCE BETWEEN THE 3 TYPES OF SORTING

Bubble, Insertion, and Selection sorts are comparison algorithms suitable for small datasets, but differ in their approach. 
- Bubble Sort swaps adjacent elements, 
- Selection Sort selects the minimum and swaps it to the front, and 
- Insertion Sort builds a sorted subarray by inserting elements. Insertion is generally the fastest for small/nearly sorted data. 


Key Differences:

= Approach: 
- Bubble Sort repeatedly bubbles the largest element to the end. 
- Selection Sort finds the smallest element and swaps it to the front. 
- Insertion Sort takes one element at a time and inserts it into its correct spot in the sorted part.

= Performance: 
- Insertion Sort is efficient for small datasets and nearly sorted data (best case). 
- Bubble and Selection Sort are generally slower.

= Swaps: 
- Bubble Sort performs a large number of swaps (every time adjacent elements are out of order). 
- Selection Sort minimizes swaps, making only one swap per pass.

= Stability: 
- Bubble and Insertion Sort are stable (maintain relative order of equal elements), while Selection Sort is typically not. 



## INSERTION VS SELECTION SORT
https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/dsa/difference-between-insertion-sort-and-selection-sort/


Insertion Sort
- Inserts an element from the unsorted part into its correct position within the already sorted part.
- Best case time: O(n) (when the array is already sorted)
- Average/worst time: O(n²)
- More writes/shifts as elements are moved to make space for the insertion (O(n²) in the worst case)
- Stable (maintains the relative order of equal elements)
- Generally performs better in practice, especially on small or partially sorted data


Selection Sort
- Finds the minimum element in the unsorted part and swaps it with the first element of the unsorted part.
- Best case time: O(n²) (always the same, regardless of input order)
- Average/worst time: O(n²)
- Fewer writes, only one swap per pass (O(n) total writes)
- Not stable (relative order of equal elements may change)
- Slower on average, but can be better if memory writes are an expensive operation.



Insertion Sort

void insertionSort(int arr[], int n) {
    int i, key, j;
    for (i = 1; i < n; i++) {
        key = arr[i]; // Store the current element
        j = i - 1;

        // Move elements of arr[0..i-1], that are greater than key, 
        // to one position ahead of their current position
        while (j >= 0 && arr[j] > key) {
            arr[j + 1] = arr[j];
            j = j - 1;
        }
        arr[j + 1] = key;
    }
}


Selection Sort

void selectionSort(int arr[], int n) {
    int i, j, min_idx, temp;
    for (i = 0; i < n - 1; i++) {
        min_idx = i;
        // Find the minimum element in the unsorted part
        for (j = i + 1; j < n; j++) {
            if (arr[j] < arr[min_idx]) {
                min_idx = j;
            }
        }
        // Swap the found minimum element with the first element of the unsorted part
        temp = arr[i];
        arr[i] = arr[min_idx];
        arr[min_idx] = temp;
    }
}



## INSERTION SORT CODE


#include <stdio.h>

void swap(int *x, int *y) {
    int temp = *x;
    *x = *y;
    *y = temp;
}

int main() {
    int arr[10] = {9,6,4,3,5,10,1,2,8,7};
    int i, j;
    
    for (i = 0; i < 9; i++) {
        int min = i;
        for (j = i + 1; j < 10; j++) {
            if (arr[j] < arr[min]) {
                min = j;
            }
        }

        if (min != i) {
            swap(&arr[min], &arr[i]);
        }
    }
    
    for (i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
        printf("%d ", arr[i]);
    }
    
    return 0;
}




